04835nam a22008175i 9780812202953DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20101999pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122029537 a10.9783/97808122029532doi  a(DE-B1597)448939  a(OCoLC)979622733  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aGR72.3 7aSOC0110002bisacsh04a398.22211 aNiles, John D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHomo Narrans :bThe Poetics and Anthropology of Oral Literature /cJohn D. Niles. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2010] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b15 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tList of Abbreviations -- t1. Making Connections -- t2. Somatic Communication -- t3. Poetry as Social Praxis -- t4. Oral Poetry Acts -- t5. Beowulf as Ritualized Discourse -- t6. Context and Loss -- t7. The Strong Tradition-Bearer -- tConclusion: Wordpower Wells from Deep in the Throat -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt would be difficult to imagine what human life would be like without stories—from myths recited by Pueblo Indian healers in the kiva, ballads sung in Slovenian market squares, folktales and legends told by the fireside in Italy, to jokes told at a dinner table in Des Moines—for it is chiefly through storytelling that people possess a past.In Homo Narrans John D. Niles explores how human beings shape their world through the stories they tell. The book vividly weaves together the study of Anglo-Saxon literature and culture with the author's own engagements in the field with some of the greatest twentieth-century singers and storytellers in the Scottish tradition. Niles ponders the nature of the storytelling impulse, the social function of narrative, and the role of individual talent in oral tradition. His investigation of the poetics of oral narrative encompasses literary works, such as the epic poems and hymns of early Greece and the Anglo-Saxon Beowulf, texts that we know only through written versions but that are grounded in oral technique.That all forms of narrative, even the most sophisticated genres of contemporary fiction, have their ultimate origin in storytelling is a point that scarcely needs to be argued. Niles's claims here are more ambitious: that oral narrative is and has long been the chief basis of culture itself, that the need to tell stories is what distinguishes humans from all other living creatures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aFolk literature. 0aOral tradition. 0aStorytelling. 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFolklore. 4aLinguistics. 4aLiterature. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220295340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812202953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812202953.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041361-8  Penn Press eBook Package Social Sciences  a978-3-11-044252-6  Penn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA1